{"title_page": "Adriatic Campaign of World War I", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of the Adriatic\n|image=Italien 1905.png\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption=The [[Adriatic Sea]] (upper right) during World War I, in an Austro-Hungarian map.\n|partof=[[World War I]], [[Mediterranean naval engagements during World War I|Battle of the Mediterranean]]\n|date=1914\u20131918\n|place=[[Adriatic Sea]]\n|result=Allied victory\n|combatant1='''[[Allies of World War I|Allies]]:'''<br/>{{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}<br/>{{navy|United Kingdom}}<br/>{{navy|France}}<br/>{{navy|Australia|1913}}<br/>{{flag|United States Navy|1912}}\n|combatant2='''[[Central Powers]]:'''<br/>{{navy|Austria-Hungary}}<br/>{{navy|German Empire}}\n|commander1=\n|commander2= \n|strength1=\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n|notes=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Mediterranean Sea 1914-1918}}\n\nThe '''Adriatic Campaign of World War I''' was a naval campaign fought between the [[Central Powers]] and the [[Mediterranean]] squadrons of [[United Kingdom|Great Britain]], [[France]], the [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]], [[Australia]] and the [[United States]].\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[First World War]] naval action in the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]] consisted mainly of Austro-Hungarian bombardments of Italy's eastern coast, and wider-ranging German and Austro-Hungarian submarine forays into the Mediterranean.\n\nAllied forces mainly limited themselves to blockading the Central Powers' navies in the Adriatic, which was successful in regards to surface units, but failed for the U-boats, which found safe harbours and easy passage into and out of the area for the whole of the war. Considered a relatively secondary part of the naval warfare of World War I, it nonetheless tied down significant forces.\n\nThe Adriatic campaign was also important because for the first time two new weapons were used successfully in warfare, viz. the [[MAS (boat)|MAS]] [[torpedo boat]] of [[Luigi Rizzo]] that sank the battleship {{SMS|Szent Istv\u00e1n||2}} and the [[human torpedo]] of [[Raffaele Rossetti]] that sank the battleship {{SMS|Viribus Unitis||6}} in 1918.\n\n==History==\n===1914===\n====Beginning of the war====\n[[File:Austro-Hungarian Dreadnoughts At Pula.jpg|thumb|right|Austro-Hungarian dreadnoughts at [[Pula|Pola]].]]\n[[File:Jean Bart (1911).jpg|right|thumb|The French [[battleship]] {{ship|French battleship|Jean Bart|1911|2}}.]]\n\nOn 6 August 1914 an [[wikt:Anglo-French|Anglo-French]] naval agreement was signed, giving [[France]] leadership of naval operations in the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. The remaining [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Mediterranean Fleet (United Kingdom)|Mediterranean forces]] - one [[armoured cruiser]], four [[light cruiser]]s, and 16 [[destroyer]]s - were placed under the control of the [[Mediterranean Fleet (France)|French Mediterranean Fleet]], and bases at both [[Gibraltar]] and [[Malta]] were opened to the French.\n\nOne day after the French declaration of war against [[Austria-Hungary]] on 11 August, a French fleet under Admiral [[Augustin Bou\u00e9 de Lapeyr\u00e8re]] arrived at Malta. He had orders to sail with all available French and British ships, pass into the Adriatic Sea, and undertake whatever operations he thought best against Austrian ports. Lapeyr\u00e8re decided to surprise Austrian vessels enforcing a blockade of [[Montenegro]]. The main Allied force comprised the French battleships {{ship|French battleship|Courbet|1911|2}} and {{ship|French battleship|Jean Bart|1911|2}}, and the cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|Jurien de la Gravi\u00e8re||2}}. Two French squadrons of [[Pre-dreadnought battleship|pre-dreadnought]]s, two squadrons of cruisers, and five destroyer squadrons were held back in support. The British support group comprised two armoured cruisers and three destroyer divisions. The Anglo-French force succeeded in cutting off and sinking the old Austro-Hungarian light cruiser {{SMS|Zenta||6}} off [[Bar, Montenegro|Bar]] on 16 August in the [[Battle of Antivari]].\n\nThroughout most of late August most of the action was simple bombardment of [[Serbia]]n and Montenegrin troops by Austrian ships. On 9 August, the pre-dreadnought {{SMS|Monarch||6}} shelled the French radio station at [[Budva]], while the destroyer {{SMS|Panther|1885|6}} shelled [[Mount Lov\u0107en]]. On 17 August, ''Monarch'' shelled a Montenegrin radio station off Bar, then another station off [[Volovica Point]] on 19 August. Meanwhile, a French squadron shelled Austrian troops on [[Prevlaka]].\n\nThe French and Montenegrin forces attempted to cause havoc also at Cattaro in September, October and November 1914, and the KuK navy was called in there also, resulting in a decisive defeat for the Allies.\n\nBoth the French and the Austrians spent much of this time laying extensive [[minefield]]s throughout the shallow waters of the Adriatic. Mostly this was done by destroyers, and at night. Several steamships ran afoul of these mines and either sunk or were damaged.\n\n====The ''Goeben''====\n{{main|Pursuit of Goeben and Breslau}}\n\nIn July, the German [[battlecruiser]] {{SMS|Goeben||6}} sailed to [[Triest]] from [[Pula|Pola]]. She and the German cruiser {{SMS|Breslau||6}} had been anchored there since the beginning of the summer. On 1 August, ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' rendezvoused at [[Brindisi]], then headed for [[Messina]] to take on coal. They left for [[Constantinople]] on 6 August, shadowed by the British cruiser {{HMS|Gloucester|1909|6}}.\n\nOn 7 August, an Austro-Hungarian Fleet\u2014consisting of six battleships, two cruisers, and 19 destroyers and torpedo boats\u2014sortied from Pola to escort ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' through Austro-Hungarian territorial waters, returned to port following day without ever making contact. ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' briefly engaged HMS ''Gloucester'' and the chase was abandoned by the British. By 10 August, both German warships were safely in the [[Dardanelles]] and heading for [[Turkey]].\n\n====Winter====\nIn November, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Cugnot||2}} managed to slip into the [[Bay of Kotor|Bocche di Cattaro]] as far as [[Topla Bay]] but was chased out by the Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Blitz}}, and the torpedo boat ''Tb 57T''. Later that month, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Curie|Q87|2}} raided the harbour barrage of Pola to wait for her chance to intrude. Two days later, on 20 December, during an attempt to sneak into the harbour she got entangled in an [[anti-submarine net]] and could not free herself. Forced to surface for fresh air, she was sunk by the Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Magnet||6}} and ''Tb 63T'', with three casualties. The Austrians raised the wreck between December 1914 and February 1915. It was then repaired and commissioned as {{SMU|U-14|Austria-Hungary|2}} in June 1915.\n\nOn 21 December, the submarine {{SMU|U-12|Austria-Hungary|2}} scored one torpedo hit on the French battleship ''Jean Bart'' off [[Sazan]] Island. The battleship had to withdraw to Malta for extensive repairs.\n\n===1915===\nIn February, the French destroyer {{ship|French destroyer|Dague||2}}\u2014while escorting the transport ''Whitehead'' to Bar\u2014was sunk after hitting a mine. Also that month, the Austrian submarine ''U-12'' was unsuccessfully attacked off [[Cape Mendra]] by a French submarine. Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Csik\u00f3s}} shelled Montenegrin positions at Bar with ''Tb 15'' and ''Tb 68F''.\n\nIn April, the Austrian {{SMU|U-5|Austria-Hungary|2}}\u2014commanded by Lt. [[Georg Ritter von Trapp]]\u2014chased the French armoured cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|Victor Hugo||2}} off [[Paxos (island)|Paxos]], but was unable to fire any torpedoes. ''U-5'' also torpedoed the French armoured cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|L\u00e9on Gambetta||2}} after a two-day chase off [[Santa Maria di Leuca]], causing 684 fatalities including Rear-Admiral S\u00e9n\u00e8s. Only 137 French sailors survived. The Austrian {{SMU|U-4|Austria-Hungary|2}} torpedoed and damaged the British light cruiser {{HMS|Dublin|1912|6}}. Also, the Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Warasdiner||6}} shelled enemy positions at Bar.\n\n====Bombardment of Ancona====\n{{Main|Bombardment of Ancona}}\n[[File:Ancona mappa.png|right|thumb|Italian province of [[Ancona]].]]\n\nWhen [[Italy]] declared war on Austria-Hungary on 23 May, the Austrian fleet was quick to act, launching several attacks on the [[Marche]] region of Italy.<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004\">{{Cite book|first=Dario|last=Petkovi\u0107|title=Ratna mornarica austro-ugarske monarhije|location= |publisher=Pula|year=2004|isbn=953-6250-80-2}}</ref> That day, the destroyer ''Dinara'' and ''Tb 53T'' bombarded the port of [[Ancona]]. The destroyer {{SMS|Lika}}\u2014on reconnaissance duty between [[Palagru\u017ea]] and [[Cape Gargano]]\u2014shelled the [[semaphore line|semaphore]] and [[radio station]] at [[Vieste]] and fired upon the Italian destroyer {{ship|Italian destroyer|Turbine|1901|2}}. On 24 May, the bulk of the Austrian fleet at Pola sailed for the Italian Adriatic coast. This included the dreadnoughts ''Viribus Unitis'', {{SMS|Tegetthoff|1912|2}}, {{SMS|Prinz Eugen|1912|2}} and eight semi and pre-dreadnoughts. The fleet bombarded several cities and other targets in and around the [[Province of Ancona]], especially damaging the port and town of Ancona itself.\n[[File:Gun turret on SMS Tegetthoff.JPG|thumb|left|[[Gun turret]] on {{SMS|Tegetthoff|1912|6}}.]]\n\nThe destroyer {{SMS|Velebit}} shelled the Italian airship ''Citt\u00e0 di Ferrara'' off Ancona. The semi-dreadnought {{SMS|Radetzky||6}} and two torpedo boats bombarded [[Potenza Picena]], then returned to Pola. The ''Radetzky''-class semi-dreadnought {{SMS|Zr\u00ednyi}}, with two torpedo boats bombarded [[Senigallia]], destroying a train and damaging a railway station and a bridge, then returned to Pola. The torpedo boat ''Tb 3'' was unsuccessfully bombed by an Italian airship. The light cruiser {{SMS|Admiral Spaun}} shelled the Italian signal station at [[Tremiti Islands|Cretaccio Island]], while the armoured cruiser {{SMS|Sankt Georg||6}}\u2014with two torpedo boats\u2014shelled [[Rimini]], damaging and derailing a freight train. The destroyer {{SMS|Streiter}} shelled the signal station near [[Torre di Mileto]]. The light cruiser {{SMS|Novara|1913|6}}, a destroyer and two torpedo boats entered [[Corsini Channel]] and shelled an Italian torpedo boat station, a semaphore station, and coastal artillery batteries.\n\nThe light cruiser {{SMS|Helgoland|1912|6}}\u2014aided by four destroyers\u2014sank the Italian destroyer ''Turbine'' in a pitched battle south of [[Pelagosa]]. The destroyer {{SMS|T\u00e1tra}} shelled the railway embankment near [[Manfredonia]] while the destroyer {{SMS|Csepel}} shelled the Manfredonia railway station.\n\nFinally, Austro-Hungarian [[flying boat]]s dropped bombs on [[Venice]] and [[airship hangar]]s at [[Chiaravalle (AN)|Chiaravalle]].\n\n====Allied raids====\nIn response, on 5 June, four different Allied task forces attacked the Austrian coast. Four Italian armoured cruisers, escorted by four French destroyers, shelled [[Cavtat]]; the British cruiser ''Dublin''\u2014escorted by five Italian destroyers\u2014shelled [[Donzella]]; the Italian light cruiser {{ship|Italian cruiser|Quarto||2}}\u2014escorted by four destroyers\u2014bombarded [[Lastovo]]; the Italian light cruiser {{ship|Italian cruiser|Nino Bixio||2}}, two Italian and two French destroyers shelled the island of [[Vis (island)|Lissa]]. On 9 June, a mixed force of British, French and Italian destroyers shelled the Austro-Hungarian signal station at [[Cape Rondini]] in [[Albania]].\n\n====The summer of 1915====\n''Sankt Georg'' and a squadron of torpedo boats bombarded Rimini on 16 June, causing minor damage. Then on 17 June, the cruisers ''Novara'' and ''Admiral Spaun'' and their escorts attacked and sank the Italian steamer ''Maria Grazia'' off [[Giulianova]]. The next day, they shelled Rimini and [[Fano]], destroying the Italian signal station there.\n\nThe summer of 1915 was a successful time for Austrian submarines as well: on 10 June, {{SMU|U-11|Austria-Hungary|2}} sank the Italian submarine {{ship|Italian submarine|Medusa|1911|2}} and torpedo boat {{ship|Italian torpedo boat|Serpente||2}}; {{SMU|U-10|Austria-Hungary|2}} sank the Italian torpedo boat ''PN 5'' on June 26 off Venice; ''U-4'' torpedoed and sank the {{ship|Italian cruiser|Giuseppe Garibaldi|1899|2}} on 18 July; and ''U-5'' captured the Greek steamer ''Cefalonia'' off Durazzo on August 29. But this was not without losses. On 13 August, {{SMU|U-3|Austria-Hungary|2}} was sunk at Brindisi by the French destroyer [[Bisson-class destroyer|''Bisson'']]<!-- {{ship|French destroyer|Bisson||2}}-->, after having been severely damaged by the Italian auxiliary cruiser {{ship|Italian auxiliary cruiser|Citt\u00e0 di Catania||2}} the day before.\n\nThe Austro-Hungarian naval air-arm also began regular bombing raids against [[Bari]] and Brindisi in June, slightly damaging the British protected cruiser {{HMS|Amethyst|1903|6}} in one such raid with machine gun fire. And the British [[Naval trawler|armed trawler]] ''Schiehallion'' was sunk by a mine. The {{ship|Italian cruiser|Amalfi||2}} was sunk off Venice by the German submarine {{SMU|UB-14||2}} on July 2. While the Italian scout cruiser {{ship|Italian cruiser|Marsala||2}} shelled [[Gravosa]] station on 18 July, the scout cruiser ''Quarto'' and three Italian destroyers attacked the Austrian installation at [[Guiparra]].\n\nSMS ''Helgoland'', seven destroyers and four torpedo boats supported an Austrian landing at Pelagosa on 28 July. The landing was repulsed by the Italian garrison, that had arrived in the island on July 11. On August 17 the light cruisers \"Helgoland\", \"Saida\" and several destroyers bombarded the island again. The water reservoir was severely damaged and the next day the Italians began the evacuation. On 17 August, one of the cruisers was unsuccessfully torpedoed by an Italian submarine on return journey. The last act of the summer was the sinking on 26 September of the Italian battleship {{ship|Italian battleship|Benedetto Brin||2}} in Brindisi harbour by Italian-speaking Austro-Hungarian [[saboteur]]s. Over 450 were killed.\n\nIn late September, the Allies established the [[Otranto Barrage]], an attempt to blockade the entrance to the Adriatic Sea at the [[Strait of Otranto]].\n\n====December====\n[[File:Monge-Marius Bar-img 3154.jpg|thumb|The French submarine ''Monge'']]\n\nIn early December, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Fresnel||2}} ran aground off the [[Bojana River]] estuary due to bad navigation, and was sunk by the Austrian destroyer ''Warasdiner''. The cruiser ''Helgoland'' and three destroyers sortie against the Otranto Barrage from 5\u201322 December and performed reconnaissance off the Albanian coast and [[San Giovanni di Medua]]. They sank an Italian picket boat, three steamships loaded with ammunition and two armed schooners ''en route'' to Northern Albania.\n\nThe light cruiser SMS ''Helgoland'' and five Tatra-class destroyers left Cattaro and headed for Durazzo late on 28 December 1915. While on passage the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Monge|1910|2}} was rammed by the cruiser SMS ''Helgoland'', and finally sunk by gunfire from the destroyer {{SMS|Balaton}}. Early the next day, the Austrians squadron opened fire on Durazzo targets, sinking some small ships. Then they ran into a minefield. The destroyer ''Lika'' was sunk and ''Triglav'' was damaged. She was taken in tow and the Austrian force sailed slowly to north.\n\nAn allied force had already sailed from Brindisi, with the aim to intercept them. It was composed of the British light cruisers HMS ''Dartmouth'' and ''Weymouth'', the Italian light cruisers RN ''Quarto'' and ''Nino Bixio'' and five French destroyers. In support of the retreating force, the Austrians despatched the armoured cruiser SMS ''Kaiser Karl VI'' and the light cruiser ''Novara'' from Cattaro. Early in the afternoon of 29 December, the forward Allied ships came into action with the retreating Austrian light squadron, which was still only halfway home. The ''Triglav'' was abandoned and scuttled and a long-range gunnery duel was fought throughout the afternoon. SMS ''Tatra'' was damaged but the Austrian light force was able to reach Cattaro safely.\n\n===1916===\nAustrian submarines sank or damaged a number of ships in 1916. ''U-11'' captured the Italian hospital ship ''King Albert'' on 18 January at San Giovanni di Medua. {{SMU|U-6|Austria-Hungary|2}} sank the French destroyer {{ship|French destroyer|Renaudin||2}} on 16 March at [[Durr\u00ebs|Durazzo]]. On 8 June, ''U-5'' torpedoed and sank the Italian troop transport ''Principe Umberto'' at [[Linguetta]]. Later, ''U-5'' fought a French-Italian destroyer group to a stalemate on 2 August, and torpedoed the Italian Q-Ship ''Pantelleria'' south of [[Taranto]] on August 14.\n\nOn 15 September 1916, the two Austro-Hungarian seaplanes L.132 and L.135 forced the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Foucault||2}} to surface by dropping bombs. L.135 finally sinks the sub while the 27 survivors were clinging to the two planes now floating, to be finally saved by the alarmed ''Tb 100M''. This was the first sinking of a submarine by airplanes in naval war history.\n\nThe very same day, the French submarine ''Amp\u00e9re'' scored two torpedo hits on the Austro-Hungarian Hospital ship ''No I'' (the former Lloyd steamer ''Elektra'') off [[Cape Planka]] (Rat Ploca), causing two fatalities. The damaged hospital ship had to be beached in Borovica Bay for further repairs.\n\nOn the night of 22/23 December, the Austro-Hungarian destroyers {{SMS|Scharfschuetze||6}}, {{SMS|Reka||2}}, {{SMS|Dinara||2}} and ''Velebit'' attacked the [[Naval drifter|drifter]]s patrolling the Otranto barrage, which applied for help to the French destroyers {{ship|French destroyer|Casque|1910|2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Protet||2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Commandant Rivi\u00e8re||2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Commandant Bory||2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Dehorter||2}} and {{ship|French destroyer|Boutefeu||2}} which were escorting a convoy from Brindisi to Taranto. Because of communication problems, only ''Casque'' and ''Commandant Rivi\u00e8re'' attacked, but ''Casque''{{'}}s boiler rooms were hit immediately and she had to slow down to {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}}. For further assistance, the Italian destroyers {{ship|Italian destroyer|Giuseppe Cesare Abba||2}}, {{ship|Italian destroyer|Ippolito Nievo||2}} and {{ship|Italian destroyer|Rosolino Pilo||2}} left Brindisi shortly followed by the British cruiser ''Gloucester'' escorted by {{ship|Italian destroyer|Impavido|1913|2}} and {{ship|Italian destroyer|Irriquieto||2}}. The French and Italian groups met during darkness, ''Giuseppe Cesare Abba'' rammed ''Casque''; some moments later, ''Boutefeu'' rammed ''Giuseppe Cesare Abba''. While the damaged vessels had to be taken into tow, the Austrians escaped in the darkness.\n\nThe return from the Otranto battle\u201415 May 1917\u2014brought the British cruiser {{HMS|Dartmouth|1910|6}} within the range of the {{SMU|UC-25||2}} which had already laid mines off Brindisi.\n\nAt 13:30, ''UC-25'' torpedoed ''Dartmouth'' approximately {{convert|36|mi|nmi km|lk=on|abbr=on}} off Brindisi, for some time the ship was considered to be lost, but was manned by a rescue crew later and finally towed into port. On hearing that ''Dartmouth'' had been torpedoed, ''Boutefeu'' went to assist, only to hit one of ''UC-25''{{'}}s mines.\n\n===1917===\nBy August 1917, Lt. Von Trapp and ''U-14'' had sunk more than {{convert|24000|LT|t|lk=on|abbr=on}} of enemy shipping, including the Italian steamer ''Milazzo'' ({{convert|11480|LT|t|abbr=on}}). ''U-4'' torpedoed the French steamer ''Italia'' near Taranto on 30 May, and on 16 November {{SMU|U-43|Austria-Hungary|2}} severely damaged the Italian steamer ''Oriona'' between Brindisi and [[Vlor\u00eb|Valona]]. On the night of 9\u201310 December, while SMS ''Wien'' and ''Budapest'' were at anchor in Trieste, two Italian MAS (motor torpedo boats) managed to penetrate the harbour defences undetected and fired several torpedoes at the two ships. ''Wien'' was struck by two torpedoes and sank in less than five minutes with the loss of 46 of her crew.\n\n===1918===\nOn 13 February, the submarine {{ship|French submarine|Bernouilli|Q83|2}} (Audry) was lost with all hands after hitting a mine off the Bocche di Cattaro.\n\nOn 22/23 April, the Austro-Hungarian {{sclass-|T\u00e1tra|destroyer|2}}s {{SMS|Triglav}}, {{SMS|Uzsok}}, {{SMS|Dukla}}, SMS ''Lika'' and SMS ''Csepel'' encountered the British destroyers {{HMS|Jackal|1911|6}} and {{HMS|Hornet|1911|2}}, the Australian {{HMAS|Torrens|D67|6}} and the French {{ship|French destroyer|Cimeterre||2}}. HMS ''Hornet'' was badly damaged in the ensuing fight but the alarm went up and the Austrians turned for home, pursued by ''Jackal'', who had lost her mainmast.\n\n====The Premuda attack====\n[[File:Affondamento Santo Stefano.jpg|thumb|right|The last moments of SMS ''Szent Istv\u00e1n'', hit by a torpedo of the Italian MAS of [[Luigi Rizzo]]]]\nAt 03:30 on the morning of 10 June 1918, the battleship ''Szent Istv\u00e1n''\u2014in the company of SMS ''Tegetthoff'' and seven other ships ''en route'' to attack the Otranto Barrage \u2014 was seen by chance and then hit by two torpedoes launched from the Italian [[MAS (ships)|MAS]]-15 [[Motor Torpedo Boat]] under Corvette Captain Luigi Rizzo near [[Premuda]] island, near [[Zadar|Zara]]. Many of the 1,087 crew were asleep, getting rested for the battle expected in a few hours. Immediate chaos soon changed into frantic efforts to save the vessel which was rapidly shipping water. SMS ''Tegetthoff'' was hit by another torpedo from a second MAS, but it did not explode.\n\nThen ''Tegetthoff''\u2014which had at first sped away from the vicinity of the torpedo attack\u2014returned and took ''Szent Istv\u00e1n'' in tow, in an attempt to reach the massive dry dock at Pula. However, the pumps were unequal to the task before them due to loss of steam pressure and the ship continued to slowly list, sinking at 06:12, almost 3 hours after being hit.<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004\"/>\n\nIt is debated that faults in the {{sclass-|Tegetthoff|battleship|0}} design - relatively low [[Displacement (fluid)|displacement]] and high [[centre of gravity]], together with the weight of twelve {{convert|305|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} main artillery - did not assist matters. However, most other battleships in The Great War which were either torpedoed or mined sank far more rapidly. There were, however, only 89 dead, partly attributed to the fact that all sailors with the K.u.K. had to learn to swim before entering active service. The attack on the Otranto Barrage was cancelled as a consequence of this attack.<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004\"/>\n\nOn 20 September, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Circ\u00e9|Q47|2}} was torpedoed {{convert|7|nmi|abbr=on}} north west of Cape Rodoni by the Austro-Hungarian submarine {{SMU|U-47|Austria-Hungary|2}} and lost with all hands.\n\n====Second Battle of Durazzo====\nOn 2 October, an allied fleet composed of Italian, British, Australian and American warships attacked the port of Durazzo, which had by that time come under Austro-Hungarian occupation, during the [[Battle of Durazzo (1918)|Second Battle of Durazzo]]. The fleet consisted of over 55 vessels along with MAS boats and supporting aircraft. Allied forces destroyed Austro-Hungarian shore batteries and defeated a small squadron of patrol craft while sustaining comparatively light damage. Durazzo was left in flames, several building, bridges and railroad targets were bombarded which forced the evacuation of the city. A week or so after the battle an allied army occupied the city without resistance.\n\n====Sinking of ''Viribus Unitis''====\nOn 1 November, the ex-Austro-Hungarian [[dreadnought]] [[flagship]] ''Viribus Unitis'' was sunk \u2014 along with the merchant-ship ''Wien''\u2014 both at anchor at Pula by  [[limpet mine]] attached by the crew of an Italian ''mignatta'' (human torpedo). The ''mignatta'' was the precursor of the human torpedo and was invented by Major of naval engineers Raffaele Rossetti.\n\nThe whole Austrian Navy was at the time being transferred to the new [[State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs]], but the Italian attackers had not been informed.\n\n==Austro-Hungarian submarines results==\n{{Main|Mediterranean U-boat Campaign (World War I)}}\n\nMany Austro-Hungarian and German U-boats operated out of the Adriatic for the whole of the war. Due to lack of cooperation of the Allies in the Mediterranean control zones, and the late institution of the convoy system, U-boats experienced substantial success throughout the first war years.<ref name=\"WILL\">{{Cite book|title=First World War|last=Willmott|first=H. P.|location=|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year=2003|pages=186\u2013187|isbn=}}</ref>\n\n[[Austro-Hungarian Navy|''K.u.K. Kriegsmarine'']] submarines sunk 117 ships during World War I, with the total of {{convert|220121|LT|t}}. The most well-known casualties were:<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004, Page 84\"/>\n* {{ship|French armoured cruiser|L\u00e9on Gambetta||2}}\n* {{ship|Italian cruiser|Giuseppe Garibaldi|1899|2}}\n* {{ship|Italian submarine|Nereide|1913|2}}\n* {{ship|French destroyer|Renaudin||2}}\n* {{ship|French destroyer|Fourche||2}}\n* {{ship|Italian destroyer|Impetuoso|1913|2}}\n* {{ship|Italian destroyer|Nembo|1901|2}}\n* {{HMS|Phoenix|1911|6}}\n* {{ship|French submarine|Circ\u00e9|Q47|2}}\n\nAlso, the ''K.u.K. Kriegsmarine'' submarines damaged the following ships:<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004, Page 84\"/>\n* {{ship|French battleship|Jean Bart|1911|2}}\n* {{HMS|Dublin|1912|6}}\n* {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sakaki|1915|2}}\n* {{HMS|Weymouth|1910|6}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"left\" style=\"margin:0 1em 0.5em 0;\"\n|+'''Tonnes sunk by K.u.K. Kriegsmarine submarines'''\n|-\n!Year\n!1914\n!1915\n!1916\n!1917\n!1918\n|-\n!Tonnage\n|13\n|22.568\n|25.716\n|112.716\n|58.902 \n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" | <small>Source:</small><ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004, Page 84\">{{Cite book|first= Dario|last=Petkovi\u0107|title=Ratna mornarica austro-ugarske monarhije|location=|publisher= Pula|year=2004|page=84|isbn=953-6250-80-2}}</ref>\n|}\n{{-}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222605/http://www.naval-history.net/WW1CampaignsSerbia.htm Serbia, Balkans & Macedonia 1914-18]\n* [http://worldatwar.net/chandelle/v1/v1n2/adriatic.html Combined Operations in the Adriatic, 1915-18]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adriatic Campaign Of World War I}}\n[[Category:Military operations of World War I involving Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean naval operations of World War I]]\n[[Category:Campaigns and theatres of World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of the Adriatic\n|image=Italien 1905.png\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption=The [[Adriatic Sea]] (upper right) during World War I, in an Austro-Hungarian map.\n|partof=[[World War I]], [[Mediterranean naval engagements during World War I|Battle of the Mediterranean]]\n|date=1914\u20131918\n|place=[[Adriatic Sea]]\n|result=Allied victory\n|combatant1='''[[Allies of World War I|Allies]]:'''<br/>{{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}<br/>{{navy|United Kingdom}}<br/>{{navy|France}}<br/>{{navy|Australia|1913}}<br/>{{flag|United States Navy|1912}}\n|combatant2='''[[Central Powers]]:'''<br/>{{navy|Austria-Hungary}}<br/>{{navy|German Empire}}\n|commander1=\n|commander2= \n|strength1=\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n|notes=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Mediterranean Sea 1914-1918}}\n\nThe '''Adriatic Campaign of World War I''' was a naval campaign fought between the [[Central Powers]] and the [[Mediterranean]] squadrons of [[United Kingdom|Great Britain]], [[France]], the [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]], [[Australia]] and the [[United States]].\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[First World War]] naval action in the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]] consisted mainly of Austro-Hungarian bombardments of Italy's eastern coast, and wider-ranging German and Austro-Hungarian submarine forays into the Mediterranean.\n\nAllied forces mainly limited themselves to blockading the Central Powers' navies in the Adriatic, which was successful in regards to surface units, but failed for the U-boats, which found safe harbours and easy passage into and out of the area for the whole of the war. Considered a relatively secondary part of the naval warfare of World War I, it nonetheless tied down significant forces.\n\nThe Adriatic campaign was also important because for the first time two new weapons were used successfully in warfare, viz. the [[MAS (boat)|MAS]] [[torpedo boat]] of [[Luigi Rizzo]] that sank the battleship {{SMS|Szent Istv\u00e1n||2}} and the [[human torpedo]] of [[Raffaele Rossetti]] that sank the battleship {{SMS|Viribus Unitis||6}} in 1918.\n\n==History==\n\n===1914===\n\n====Beginning of the war====\n[[File:Austro-Hungarian Dreadnoughts At Pula.jpg|thumb|right|Austro-Hungarian dreadnoughts at [[Pula|Pola]].]]\n[[File:Jean Bart (1911).jpg|right|thumb|The French [[battleship]] {{ship|French battleship|Jean Bart|1911|2}}.]]\n\nOn 6 August 1914 an [[wikt:Anglo-French|Anglo-French]] naval agreement was signed, giving [[France]] leadership of naval operations in the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. The remaining [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Mediterranean Fleet (United Kingdom)|Mediterranean forces]] - one [[armoured cruiser]], four [[light cruiser]]s, and 16 [[destroyer]]s - were placed under the control of the [[Mediterranean Fleet (France)|French Mediterranean Fleet]], and bases at both [[Gibraltar]] and [[Malta]] were opened to the French.\n\nOne day after the French declaration of war against [[Austria-Hungary]] on 11 August, a French fleet under Admiral [[Augustin Bou\u00e9 de Lapeyr\u00e8re]] arrived at Malta. He had orders to sail with all available French and British ships, pass into the Adriatic Sea, and undertake whatever operations he thought best against Austrian ports. Lapeyr\u00e8re decided to surprise Austrian vessels enforcing a blockade of [[Montenegro]]. The main Allied force comprised the French battleships {{ship|French battleship|Courbet|1911|2}} and {{ship|French battleship|Jean Bart|1911|2}}, and the cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|Jurien de la Gravi\u00e8re||2}}. Two French squadrons of [[Pre-dreadnought battleship|pre-dreadnought]]s, two squadrons of cruisers, and five destroyer squadrons were held back in support. The British support group comprised two armoured cruisers and three destroyer divisions. The Anglo-French force succeeded in cutting off and sinking the old Austro-Hungarian light cruiser {{SMS|Zenta||6}} off [[Bar, Montenegro|Bar]] on 16 August in the [[Battle of Antivari]].\n\nThroughout most of late August most of the action was simple bombardment of [[Serbia]]n and Montenegrin troops by Austrian ships. On 9 August, the pre-dreadnought {{SMS|Monarch||6}} shelled the French radio station at [[Budva]], while the destroyer {{SMS|Panther|1885|6}} shelled [[Mount Lov\u0107en]]. On 17 August, ''Monarch'' shelled a Montenegrin radio station off Bar, then another station off [[Volovica Point]] on 19 August. Meanwhile, a French squadron shelled Austrian troops on [[Prevlaka]].\n\nThe French and Montenegrin forces attempted to cause havoc also at Cattaro in September, October and November 1914, and the KuK navy was called in there also, resulting in a decisive defeat for the Allies.\n\nBoth the French and the Austrians spent much of this time laying extensive [[minefield]]s throughout the shallow waters of the Adriatic. Mostly this was done by destroyers, and at night. Several steamships ran afoul of these mines and either sunk or were damaged.\n\n====The ''Goeben''====\n{{main|Pursuit of Goeben and Breslau}}\n\nIn July, the German [[battlecruiser]] {{SMS|Goeben||6}} sailed to [[Triest]] from [[Pula|Pola]]. She and the German cruiser {{SMS|Breslau||6}} had been anchored there since the beginning of the summer. On 1 August, ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' rendezvoused at [[Brindisi]], then headed for [[Messina]] to take on coal. They left for [[Constantinople]] on 6 August, shadowed by the British cruiser {{HMS|Gloucester|1909|6}}.\n\nOn 7 August, an Austro-Hungarian Fleet\u2014consisting of six battleships, two cruisers, and 19 destroyers and torpedo boats\u2014sortied from Pola to escort ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' through Austro-Hungarian territorial waters, returned to port following day without ever making contact. ''Goeben'' and ''Breslau'' briefly engaged HMS ''Gloucester'' and the chase was abandoned by the British. By 10 August, both German warships were safely in the [[Dardanelles]] and heading for [[Turkey]].\n\n====Winter====\nIn November, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Cugnot||2}} managed to slip into the [[Bay of Kotor|Bocche di Cattaro]] as far as [[Topla Bay]] but was chased out by the Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Blitz}}, and the torpedo boat ''Tb 57T''. Later that month, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Curie|Q87|2}} raided the harbour barrage of Pola to wait for her chance to intrude. Two days later, on 20 December, during an attempt to sneak into the harbour she got entangled in an [[anti-submarine net]] and could not free herself. Forced to surface for fresh air, she was sunk by the Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Magnet||6}} and ''Tb 63T'', with three casualties. The Austrians raised the wreck between December 1914 and February 1915. It was then repaired and commissioned as {{SMU|U-14|Austria-Hungary|2}} in June 1915.\n\nOn 21 December, the submarine {{SMU|U-12|Austria-Hungary|2}} scored one torpedo hit on the French battleship ''Jean Bart'' off [[Sazan]] Island. The battleship had to withdraw to Malta for extensive repairs.\n\n===1915===\nIn February, the French destroyer {{ship|French destroyer|Dague||2}}\u2014while escorting the transport ''Whitehead'' to Bar\u2014was sunk after hitting a mine. Also that month, the Austrian submarine ''U-12'' was unsuccessfully attacked off [[Cape Mendra]] by a French submarine. Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Csik\u00f3s}} shelled Montenegrin positions at Bar with ''Tb 15'' and ''Tb 68F''.\n\nIn April, the Austrian {{SMU|U-5|Austria-Hungary|2}}\u2014commanded by Lt. [[Georg Ritter von Trapp]]\u2014chased the French armoured cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|Victor Hugo||2}} off [[Paxos (island)|Paxos]], but was unable to fire any torpedoes. ''U-5'' also torpedoed the French armoured cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|L\u00e9on Gambetta||2}} after a two-day chase off [[Santa Maria di Leuca]], causing 684 fatalities including Rear-Admiral S\u00e9n\u00e8s. Only 137 French sailors survived. The Austrian {{SMU|U-4|Austria-Hungary|2}} torpedoed and damaged the British light cruiser {{HMS|Dublin|1912|6}}. Also, the Austrian destroyer {{SMS|Warasdiner||6}} shelled enemy positions at Bar.\n\n====Bombardment of Ancona====\n{{Main|Bombardment of Ancona}}\n[[File:Ancona mappa.png|right|thumb|Italian province of [[Ancona]].]]\n\nWhen [[Italy]] declared war on Austria-Hungary on 23 May, the Austrian fleet was quick to act, launching several attacks on the [[Marche]] region of Italy.<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004\">{{Cite book|first=Dario|last=Petkovi\u0107|title=Ratna mornarica austro-ugarske monarhije|location= |publisher=Pula|year=2004|isbn=953-6250-80-2}}</ref> That day, the destroyer ''Dinara'' and ''Tb 53T'' bombarded the port of [[Ancona]]. The destroyer {{SMS|Lika}}\u2014on reconnaissance duty between [[Palagru\u017ea]] and [[Cape Gargano]]\u2014shelled the [[semaphore line|semaphore]] and [[radio station]] at [[Vieste]] and fired upon the Italian destroyer {{ship|Italian destroyer|Turbine|1901|2}}. On 24 May, the bulk of the Austrian fleet at Pola sailed for the Italian Adriatic coast. This included the dreadnoughts ''Viribus Unitis'', {{SMS|Tegetthoff|1912|2}}, {{SMS|Prinz Eugen|1912|2}} and eight semi and pre-dreadnoughts. The fleet bombarded several cities and other targets in and around the [[Province of Ancona]], especially damaging the port and town of Ancona itself.\n[[File:Gun turret on SMS Tegetthoff.JPG|thumb|left|[[Gun turret]] on {{SMS|Tegetthoff|1912|6}}.]]\n\nThe destroyer {{SMS|Velebit}} shelled the Italian airship ''Citt\u00e0 di Ferrara'' off Ancona. The semi-dreadnought {{SMS|Radetzky||6}} and two torpedo boats bombarded [[Potenza Picena]], then returned to Pola. The ''Radetzky''-class semi-dreadnought {{SMS|Zr\u00ednyi}}, with two torpedo boats bombarded [[Senigallia]], destroying a train and damaging a railway station and a bridge, then returned to Pola. The torpedo boat ''Tb 3'' was unsuccessfully bombed by an Italian airship. The light cruiser {{SMS|Admiral Spaun}} shelled the Italian signal station at [[Tremiti Islands|Cretaccio Island]], while the armoured cruiser {{SMS|Sankt Georg||6}}\u2014with two torpedo boats\u2014shelled [[Rimini]], damaging and derailing a freight train. The destroyer {{SMS|Streiter}} shelled the signal station near [[Torre di Mileto]]. The light cruiser {{SMS|Novara|1913|6}}, a destroyer and two torpedo boats entered [[Corsini Channel]] and shelled an Italian torpedo boat station, a semaphore station, and coastal artillery batteries.\n\nThe light cruiser {{SMS|Helgoland|1912|6}}\u2014aided by four destroyers\u2014sank the Italian destroyer ''Turbine'' in a pitched battle south of [[Pelagosa]]. The destroyer {{SMS|T\u00e1tra}} shelled the railway embankment near [[Manfredonia]] while the destroyer {{SMS|Csepel}} shelled the Manfredonia railway station.\n\nFinally, Austro-Hungarian [[flying boat]]s dropped bombs on [[Venice]] and [[airship hangar]]s at [[Chiaravalle (AN)|Chiaravalle]].\n\n====Allied raids====\nIn response, on 5 June, four different Allied task forces attacked the Austrian coast. Four Italian armoured cruisers, escorted by four French destroyers, shelled [[Cavtat]]; the British cruiser ''Dublin''\u2014escorted by five Italian destroyers\u2014shelled [[Donzella]]; the Italian light cruiser {{ship|Italian cruiser|Quarto||2}}\u2014escorted by four destroyers\u2014bombarded [[Lastovo]]; the Italian light cruiser {{ship|Italian cruiser|Nino Bixio||2}}, two Italian and two French destroyers shelled the island of [[Vis (island)|Lissa]]. On 9 June, a mixed force of British, French and Italian destroyers shelled the Austro-Hungarian signal station at [[Cape Rondini]] in [[Albania]].\n\n====The summer of 1915====\n''Sankt Georg'' and a squadron of torpedo boats bombarded Rimini on 16 June, causing minor damage. Then on 17 June, the cruisers ''Novara'' and ''Admiral Spaun'' and their escorts attacked and sank the Italian steamer ''Maria Grazia'' off [[Giulianova]]. The next day, they shelled Rimini and [[Fano]], destroying the Italian signal station there.\n\nThe summer of 1915 was a successful time for Austrian submarines as well: on 10 June, {{SMU|U-11|Austria-Hungary|2}} sank the Italian submarine {{ship|Italian submarine|Medusa|1911|2}} and torpedo boat {{ship|Italian torpedo boat|Serpente||2}}; {{SMU|U-10|Austria-Hungary|2}} sank the Italian torpedo boat ''PN 5'' on June 26 off Venice; ''U-4'' torpedoed and sank the {{ship|Italian cruiser|Giuseppe Garibaldi|1899|2}} on 18 July; and ''U-5'' captured the Greek steamer ''Cefalonia'' off Durazzo on August 29. But this was not without losses. On 13 August, {{SMU|U-3|Austria-Hungary|2}} was sunk at Brindisi by the French destroyer [[Bisson-class destroyer|''Bisson'']]<!-- {{ship|French destroyer|Bisson||2}}-->, after having been severely damaged by the Italian auxiliary cruiser {{ship|Italian auxiliary cruiser|Citt\u00e0 di Catania||2}} the day before.\n\nThe Austro-Hungarian naval air-arm also began regular bombing raids against [[Bari]] and Brindisi in June, slightly damaging the British protected cruiser {{HMS|Amethyst|1903|6}} in one such raid with machine gun fire. And the British [[Naval trawler|armed trawler]] ''Schiehallion'' was sunk by a mine. The {{ship|Italian cruiser|Amalfi||2}} was sunk off Venice by the German submarine {{SMU|UB-14||2}} on July 2. While the Italian scout cruiser {{ship|Italian cruiser|Marsala||2}} shelled [[Gravosa]] station on 18 July, the scout cruiser ''Quarto'' and three Italian destroyers attacked the Austrian installation at [[Guiparra]].\n\nSMS ''Helgoland'', seven destroyers and four torpedo boats supported an Austrian landing at Pelagosa on 28 July. The landing was repulsed by the Italian garrison, that had arrived in the island on July 11. On August 17 the light cruisers \"Helgoland\", \"Saida\" and several destroyers bombarded the island again. The water reservoir was severely damaged and the next day the Italians began the evacuation. On 17 August, one of the cruisers was unsuccessfully torpedoed by an Italian submarine on return journey. The last act of the summer was the sinking on 26 September of the Italian battleship {{ship|Italian battleship|Benedetto Brin||2}} in Brindisi harbour by Italian-speaking Austro-Hungarian [[saboteur]]s. Over 450 were killed.\n\nIn late September, the Allies established the [[Otranto Barrage]], an attempt to blockade the entrance to the Adriatic Sea at the [[Strait of Otranto]].\n\n====December====\n[[File:Monge-Marius Bar-img 3154.jpg|thumb|The French submarine ''Monge'']]\n\nIn early December, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Fresnel||2}} ran aground off the [[Bojana River]] estuary due to bad navigation, and was sunk by the Austrian destroyer ''Warasdiner''. The cruiser ''Helgoland'' and three destroyers sortie against the Otranto Barrage from 5\u201322 December and performed reconnaissance off the Albanian coast and [[San Giovanni di Medua]]. They sank an Italian picket boat, three steamships loaded with ammunition and two armed schooners ''en route'' to Northern Albania.\n\nThe light cruiser SMS ''Helgoland'' and five Tatra-class destroyers left Cattaro and headed for Durazzo late on 28 December 1915. While on passage the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Monge|1910|2}} was rammed by the cruiser SMS ''Helgoland'', and finally sunk by gunfire from the destroyer {{SMS|Balaton}}. Early the next day, the Austrians squadron opened fire on Durazzo targets, sinking some small ships. Then they ran into a minefield. The destroyer ''Lika'' was sunk and ''Triglav'' was damaged. She was taken in tow and the Austrian force sailed slowly to north.\n\nAn allied force had already sailed from Brindisi, with the aim to intercept them. It was composed of the British light cruisers HMS ''Dartmouth'' and ''Weymouth'', the Italian light cruisers RN ''Quarto'' and ''Nino Bixio'' and five French destroyers. In support of the retreating force, the Austrians despatched the armoured cruiser SMS ''Kaiser Karl VI'' and the light cruiser ''Novara'' from Cattaro. Early in the afternoon of 29 December, the forward Allied ships came into action with the retreating Austrian light squadron, which was still only halfway home. The ''Triglav'' was abandoned and scuttled and a long-range gunnery duel was fought throughout the afternoon. SMS ''Tatra'' was damaged but the Austrian light force was able to reach Cattaro safely.\n\n===1916===\nAustrian submarines sank or damaged a number of ships in 1916. ''U-11'' captured the Italian hospital ship ''King Albert'' on 18 January at San Giovanni di Medua. {{SMU|U-6|Austria-Hungary|2}} sank the French destroyer {{ship|French destroyer|Renaudin||2}} on 16 March at [[Durr\u00ebs|Durazzo]]. On 8 June, ''U-5'' torpedoed and sank the Italian troop transport ''Principe Umberto'' at [[Linguetta]]. Later, ''U-5'' fought a French-Italian destroyer group to a stalemate on 2 August, and torpedoed the Italian Q-Ship ''Pantelleria'' south of [[Taranto]] on August 14.\n\nOn 15 September 1916, the two Austro-Hungarian seaplanes L.132 and L.135 forced the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Foucault||2}} to surface by dropping bombs. L.135 finally sinks the sub while the 27 survivors were clinging to the two planes now floating, to be finally saved by the alarmed ''Tb 100M''. This was the first sinking of a submarine by airplanes in naval war history.\n\nThe very same day, the French submarine ''Amp\u00e9re'' scored two torpedo hits on the Austro-Hungarian Hospital ship ''No I'' (the former Lloyd steamer ''Elektra'') off [[Cape Planka]] (Rat Ploca), causing two fatalities. The damaged hospital ship had to be beached in Borovica Bay for further repairs.\n\nOn the night of 22/23 December, the Austro-Hungarian destroyers {{SMS|Scharfschuetze||6}}, {{SMS|Reka||2}}, {{SMS|Dinara||2}} and ''Velebit'' attacked the [[Naval drifter|drifter]]s patrolling the Otranto barrage, which applied for help to the French destroyers {{ship|French destroyer|Casque|1910|2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Protet||2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Commandant Rivi\u00e8re||2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Commandant Bory||2}}, {{ship|French destroyer|Dehorter||2}} and {{ship|French destroyer|Boutefeu||2}} which were escorting a convoy from Brindisi to Taranto. Because of communication problems, only ''Casque'' and ''Commandant Rivi\u00e8re'' attacked, but ''Casque''{{'}}s boiler rooms were hit immediately and she had to slow down to {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}}. For further assistance, the Italian destroyers {{ship|Italian destroyer|Giuseppe Cesare Abba||2}}, {{ship|Italian destroyer|Ippolito Nievo||2}} and {{ship|Italian destroyer|Rosolino Pilo||2}} left Brindisi shortly followed by the British cruiser ''Gloucester'' escorted by {{ship|Italian destroyer|Impavido|1913|2}} and {{ship|Italian destroyer|Irriquieto||2}}. The French and Italian groups met during darkness, ''Giuseppe Cesare Abba'' rammed ''Casque''; some moments later, ''Boutefeu'' rammed ''Giuseppe Cesare Abba''. While the damaged vessels had to be taken into tow, the Austrians escaped in the darkness.\n\nThe return from the Otranto battle\u201415 May 1917\u2014brought the British cruiser {{HMS|Dartmouth|1910|6}} within the range of the {{SMU|UC-25||2}} which had already laid mines off Brindisi.\n\nAt 13:30, ''UC-25'' torpedoed ''Dartmouth'' approximately {{convert|36|mi|nmi km|lk=on|abbr=on}} off Brindisi, for some time the ship was considered to be lost, but was manned by a rescue crew later and finally towed into port. On hearing that ''Dartmouth'' had been torpedoed, ''Boutefeu'' went to assist, only to hit one of ''UC-25''{{'}}s mines.\n\n===1917===\nBy August 1917, Lt. Von Trapp and ''U-14'' had sunk more than {{convert|24000|LT|t|lk=on|abbr=on}} of enemy shipping, including the Italian steamer ''Milazzo'' ({{convert|11480|LT|t|abbr=on}}). ''U-4'' torpedoed the French steamer ''Italia'' near Taranto on 30 May, and on 16 November {{SMU|U-43|Austria-Hungary|2}} severely damaged the Italian steamer ''Oriona'' between Brindisi and [[Vlor\u00eb|Valona]]. On the night of 9\u201310 December, while SMS ''Wien'' and ''Budapest'' were at anchor in Trieste, two Italian MAS (motor torpedo boats) managed to penetrate the harbour defences undetected and fired several torpedoes at the two ships. ''Wien'' was struck by two torpedoes and sank in less than five minutes with the loss of 46 of her crew.\n\n===1918===\nOn 13 February, the submarine {{ship|French submarine|Bernouilli|Q83|2}} (Audry) was lost with all hands after hitting a mine off the Bocche di Cattaro.\n\nOn 22/23 April, the Austro-Hungarian {{sclass-|T\u00e1tra|destroyer|2}}s {{SMS|Triglav}}, {{SMS|Uzsok}}, {{SMS|Dukla}}, SMS ''Lika'' and SMS ''Csepel'' encountered the British destroyers {{HMS|Jackal|1911|6}} and {{HMS|Hornet|1911|2}}, the Australian {{HMAS|Torrens|D67|6}} and the French {{ship|French destroyer|Cimeterre||2}}. HMS ''Hornet'' was badly damaged in the ensuing fight but the alarm went up and the Austrians turned for home, pursued by ''Jackal'', who had lost her mainmast.\n\n====The Premuda attack====\n[[File:Affondamento Santo Stefano.jpg|thumb|right|The last moments of SMS ''Szent Istv\u00e1n'', hit by a torpedo of the Italian MAS of [[Luigi Rizzo]]]]\n\nAt 03:30 on the morning of 10 June 1918, the battleship ''Szent Istv\u00e1n''\u2014in the company of SMS ''Tegetthoff'' and seven other ships ''en route'' to attack the Otranto Barrage \u2014 was seen by chance and then hit by two torpedoes launched from the Italian [[MAS (ships)|MAS]]-15 [[Motor Torpedo Boat]] under Corvette Captain Luigi Rizzo near [[Premuda]] island, near [[Zadar|Zara]]. Many of the 1,087 crew were asleep, getting rested for the battle expected in a few hours. Immediate chaos soon changed into frantic efforts to save the vessel which was rapidly shipping water. SMS ''Tegetthoff'' was hit by another torpedo from a second MAS, but it did not explode.\n\nThen ''Tegetthoff''\u2014which had at first sped away from the vicinity of the torpedo attack\u2014returned and took ''Szent Istv\u00e1n'' in tow, in an attempt to reach the massive dry dock at Pula. However, the pumps were unequal to the task before them due to loss of steam pressure and the ship continued to slowly list, sinking at 06:12, almost 3 hours after being hit.<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004\"/>\n\nIt is debated that faults in the {{sclass-|Tegetthoff|battleship|0}} design - relatively low [[Displacement (fluid)|displacement]] and high [[centre of gravity]], together with the weight of twelve {{convert|305|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} main artillery - did not assist matters. However, most other battleships in The Great War which were either torpedoed or mined sank far more rapidly. There were, however, only 89 dead, partly attributed to the fact that all sailors with the K.u.K. had to learn to swim before entering active service. The attack on the Otranto Barrage was cancelled as a consequence of this attack.<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004\"/>\n\nOn 20 September, the French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Circ\u00e9|Q47|2}} was torpedoed {{convert|7|nmi|abbr=on}} north west of Cape Rodoni by the Austro-Hungarian submarine {{SMU|U-47|Austria-Hungary|2}} and lost with all hands.\n\n====Second Battle of Durazzo====\nOn 2 October, an allied fleet composed of Italian, British, Australian and American warships attacked the port of Durazzo, which had by that time come under Austro-Hungarian occupation, during the [[Battle of Durazzo (1918)|Second Battle of Durazzo]]. The fleet consisted of over 55 vessels along with MAS boats and supporting aircraft. Allied forces destroyed Austro-Hungarian shore batteries and defeated a small squadron of patrol craft while sustaining comparatively light damage. Durazzo was left in flames, several building, bridges and railroad targets were bombarded which forced the evacuation of the city. A week or so after the battle an allied army occupied the city without resistance.\n\n====Sinking of ''Viribus Unitis''====\nOn 1 November, the ex-Austro-Hungarian [[dreadnought]] [[flagship]] ''Viribus Unitis'' was sunk \u2014 along with the merchant-ship ''Wien''\u2014 both at anchor at Pula by  [[limpet mine]] attached by the crew of an Italian ''mignatta'' (human torpedo). The ''mignatta'' was the precursor of the human torpedo and was invented by Major of naval engineers Raffaele Rossetti.\n\nThe whole Austrian Navy was at the time being transferred to the new [[State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs]], but the Italian attackers had not been informed.\n\n==Austro-Hungarian submarines results==\n{{Main|Mediterranean U-boat Campaign (World War I)}}\n\nMany Austro-Hungarian and German U-boats operated out of the Adriatic for the whole of the war. Due to lack of cooperation of the Allies in the Mediterranean control zones, and the late institution of the convoy system, U-boats experienced substantial success throughout the first war years.<ref name=\"WILL\">{{Cite book|title=First World War|last=Willmott|first=H. P.|location=|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year=2003|pages=186\u2013187|isbn=}}</ref>\n\n[[Austro-Hungarian Navy|''K.u.K. Kriegsmarine'']] submarines sunk 117 ships during World War I, with the total of {{convert|220121|LT|t}}. The most well-known casualties were:<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004, Page 84\"/>\n\n* {{ship|French armoured cruiser|L\u00e9on Gambetta||2}}\n* {{ship|Italian cruiser|Giuseppe Garibaldi|1899|2}}\n* {{ship|Italian submarine|Nereide|1913|2}}\n* {{ship|French destroyer|Renaudin||2}}\n* {{ship|French destroyer|Fourche||2}}\n* {{ship|Italian destroyer|Impetuoso|1913|2}}\n* {{ship|Italian destroyer|Nembo|1901|2}}\n* {{HMS|Phoenix|1911|6}}\n* {{ship|French submarine|Circ\u00e9|Q47|2}}\n\nAlso, the ''K.u.K. Kriegsmarine'' submarines damaged the following ships:<ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004, Page 84\"/>\n* {{ship|French battleship|Jean Bart|1911|2}}\n* {{HMS|Dublin|1912|6}}\n* {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sakaki|1915|2}}\n* {{HMS|Weymouth|1910|6}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"left\" style=\"margin:0 1em 0.5em 0;\"\n|+'''Tonnes sunk by K.u.K. Kriegsmarine submarines'''\n|-\n!Year\n!1914\n!1915\n!1916\n!1917\n!1918\n|-\n!Tonnage\n|13\n|22.568\n|25.716\n|112.716\n|58.902 \n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" | <small>Source:</small><ref name=\"Dario Petkovi\u0107 2004, Page 84\">{{Cite book|first= Dario|last=Petkovi\u0107|title=Ratna mornarica austro-ugarske monarhije|location=|publisher= Pula|year=2004|page=84|isbn=953-6250-80-2}}</ref>\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222605/http://www.naval-history.net/WW1CampaignsSerbia.htm Serbia, Balkans & Macedonia 1914-18]\n* [http://worldatwar.net/chandelle/v1/v1n2/adriatic.html Combined Operations in the Adriatic, 1915-18]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adriatic Campaign Of World War I}}\n[[Category:Military operations of World War I involving Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean naval operations of World War I]]\n[[Category:Campaigns and theatres of World War I]]\n", "name_user": "YTRK", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adriatic_Campaign_of_World_War_I"}
{"title_page": "Kakegurui (2017 TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{About|the anime series that started in 2017|the live-action drama in 2018|Kakegurui#Drama}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name    = Kakegurui (anime)\n| image        =\n| genre        = [[Drama]] [[Comedy]]\n| show_name_2  = Kakegurui \u00d7\u00d7 (season 2)\n| developer    =\n| based_on     = {{Based on|''[[Kakegurui \u2013 Compulsive Gambler|Kakegurui]]''|Homura Kawamoto<br /> T\u014dru Naomura}}\n| starring     =\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme    =\n| endtheme     =\n| country      = Japan\n| language     = Japanese\n| num_seasons  = 2\n| num_episodes = 24\n| executive producer =\n| camera       =\n| runtime      = 24-30 minutes\n| company      =\n| channel      = [[Tokyo MX]] [[Mainichi Broadcasting System]]\n| picture_format = [[1080p]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired  = {{Start date|2017|7|1}}\n| last_aired   = {{End date|2019|3|26}}\n| related = [[Kakegurui (2018 TV series)]]\n| website      = http://netflix.com/title/80175351\n}}\n'''''Kakegurui''''' is an [[anime]] series adapted from the [[Kakegurui \u2013 Compulsive Gambler|manga of the same title]] written by Homura Kawamoto and illustrated by T\u014dru Naomura. The anime television series is animated by [[MAPPA (studio)|MAPPA]]. It aired from July 1 to September 23, 2017, on [[Tokyo MX]], [[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]] and other channels. A second season titled '''''Kakegurui \u00d7\u00d7''''' aired from January 8 to March 26, 2019. The cast reprised their roles, and the staff returned for the second season. [[Netflix]] began streaming the series in 2018.\n\n==History==\n===Development===\n''Kakegurui'' is an [[anime]] series adapted from the [[Kakegurui \u2013 Compulsive Gambler|manga of the same title]] written by Homura Kawamoto and illustrated by T\u014dru Naomura. The anime television series is animated by [[MAPPA (studio)|MAPPA]].\n\nThe music videos for the opening and closing themes were released in 2017.<ref>[https://manga.tokyo/news/kakegurui-opening-and-ending-official-music-videos-released-kyomaf-talk-event-announced/ manga.tokyo]</ref>\n\n===First season release===\nThe first season of ''Kakegurui'' aired from July 1 to September 23, 2017, on [[Tokyo MX]], [[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]] and other channels. Yuichiro Hayashi directed the series, [[Yasuko Kobayashi]] handled the scripts, and Manabu Akita handled the character designs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-02-16/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-manga-gets-anime-by-garo-team/.111839|title=Kakegurui - Compulsive Gambler Manga Gets Anime by Garo Team|website=Anime News Network|date=February 17, 2017|accessdate=May 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505230759/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-02-16/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-manga-gets-anime-by-garo-team/.111839|archivedate=May 5, 2017}}</ref> TECHNOBOYS PULCRAFT GREEN-FUND composed the music for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-03-22/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-anime-video-confirms-summer-debut-technoboys-pulcraft-green-fund-music/.113735|title=Kakegurui - Compulsive Gambler Anime's Video Confirms Summer Debut, TECHNOBOYS PULCRAFT GREEN-FUND Music|website=Anime News Network|date=March 22, 2017|accessdate=May 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325125728/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-03-22/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-anime-video-confirms-summer-debut-technoboys-pulcraft-green-fund-music/.113735|archivedate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> The opening theme is \"Deal with the Devil\", performed by [[Tia (singer)|Tia]]. D-Selections performed the ending theme \"LAYon-theLINE\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-09/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-anime-reveals-2nd-promo-video-theme-song-artists/.117245|title=Kakegurui - Compulsive Gambler Anime Reveals 2nd Promo Video, Theme Song Artists|website=Anime News Network|date=June 9, 2017|accessdate=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610134846/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-09/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-anime-reveals-2nd-promo-video-theme-song-artists/.117245|archivedate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> The first season is licensed and streamed by [[Netflix]], first in 2018,<ref>[https://sbindependent.org/first-impression-kakegurui-reaction-madness-behind-gambling/ sbindependent.org]</ref> and ran for 12 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2017-03-28/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-series-premieres-in-july-has-12-episodes/.113849|title=Kakegurui Compulsive Gambler Series Premieres in July, Has 12 Episodes|website=Anime News Network|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=May 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508225102/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2017-03-28/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-series-premieres-in-july-has-12-episodes/.113849|archivedate=May 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-09/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-anime-reveals-2nd-promo-video-theme-song-artists/.117245|title=Kakegurui - Compulsive Gambler Anime Reveals 2nd Promo Video, Theme Song Artists|website=Anime News Network|date=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610134846/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-09/kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-anime-reveals-2nd-promo-video-theme-song-artists/.117245|archivedate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Anime Limited]] acquired the series for release on home video in the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://animeuknews.net/2018/02/anime-limited-acquires-kakegurui-compulsive-gambler-season-1-for-uk-home-video/|title=Anime Limited Acquires Kakegurui: Compulsive Gambler Season 1 for UK Home Video!|date=February 6, 2018|publisher=Anime UK News|accessdate=September 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nConcerning reception of the first season, ''[[Collider]]'' gave the anime series release on Netflix a negative review, although did note it was catered to fans of gambling and sexualized characters.<ref>[https://collider.com/kakegurui-review-netflix/ collider.com]</ref> About the anime first season, ''GoombaStomp'' wrote \"''Kakegurui'' is a sometimes silly, often intoxicating anime that had all the makings of something truly special...regardless of its shortcomings, ''Kakegurui'' is worth being watched if just for its gripping gambling bouts alone.\"<ref>[https://goombastomp.com/kakegurui-review/ goombastomp.com]</ref>\n\n===Second season release===\nIn August 2018, it was announced that ''Kakegurui'' season 2 would debut in Japan in January 2019.<ref>[https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-08-21/kakegurui-anime-2nd-season-to-debut-in-january-with-returning-staff-cast/.135751 animenewsnetwork.com]</ref>A second season<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-01-06/kakegurui-anime-gets-2nd-season/.126120|title=Kakegurui Anime Gets 2nd Season|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 7, 2018|accessdate=January 7, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106174154/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-01-06/kakegurui-anime-gets-2nd-season/.126120|archivedate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> titled ''Kakegurui \u00d7\u00d7'' aired from January 8 to March 26, 2019. The cast reprised their roles, and the staff returned for the second season. Kiyoshi Matsuda joined Yuichiro Hayashi as director for the second season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kakegurui Anime's 2nd Season to Debut in January With Returning Staff, Cast|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-08-21/kakegurui-anime-2nd-season-to-debut-in-january-with-returning-staff-cast/.135751|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=August 21, 2018|date=August 21, 2018}}</ref> For season 2 of the anime, Yasuko Kobayashi and Manabu Akita served respectively as writer and character designer, with MAPPA handling animation for the second season as well.<ref>[https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-25/junna-performs-opening-theme-for-kakegurui-anime-2nd-season/.139924 animenewsnetwork.com]</ref> [[Mitsuki Saiga]] was added to the season 2 cast, voicing the new character Miloslava Honebami.<ref>[https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-02/kakegurui-anime-2nd-season-casts-mitsuki-saiga/.140269 animenewsnetwork.com]</ref> The second season's opening theme song is {{nihongo|\"Kono Yubi Tomare\"|\u30b3\u30ce\u30e6\u30d3\u30c8\u30de\u30ec}} performed by [[Junna (singer)|JUNNA]],<ref>{{cite web|title=JUNNA Performs Opening Theme for Kakegurui Anime's 2nd Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-25/junna-performs-opening-theme-for-kakegurui-anime-2nd-season/.139924|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=November 25, 2018|date=November 25, 2018}}</ref> while the ending theme is \"AlegriA\" performed by D-selections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-05/kakegurui-anime-2nd-season-video-reveals-more-cast-ending-song-info-january-8-debut/.140440|title=Kakegurui Anime's 2nd Season Video Reveals More Cast, Ending Song Info, January 8 Debut|website=Anime News Network|date=December 5, 2018|accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref> The second season ran for 12 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2019-01-14/kakegurui-anime-2nd-season-listed-with-12-episodes/.142045|title=Kakegurui Anime's 2nd Season Listed With 12 Episodes|website=Anime News Network|date=January 14, 2019|accessdate=January 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Thrillist]]'', both the first season and ''Kakegurui XX'' were aired on Netflix in 2018.<ref>[https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/kakegurui-season-2-review-netflix-anime thrillist.com]</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Saori Hayami]] as Yumeko Jabami\n* [[Minami Tanaka]] as Meari Saotome\n* Tatsuya Tokutake as Ry\u014dta Suzui\n* [[Y\u016bki Wakai]] as Itsuki Sumeragi\n* Karin Nanami as Yuriko Nishinot\u014din\n* [[Mariya Ise]] as Midari Ikishima\n* [[Y\u016b Serizawa]] as Yumemi Yumemite\n* [[Tomokazu Sugita]] as Kaede Many\u016bda\n* Mayu Udono as Runa Yomozuki\n* [[Ayaka Fukuhara]] as Sayaka Igarashi\n* [[Miyuki Sawashiro]] as Kirari Momobami\n\n'''Season 2 only'''\n* [[Mitsuki Saiga]] as Miloslava Honebami\n\n==Episode list==\n===Kakegurui===\n{|class=\"plainrowheaders wikitable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto; background:#FFF;\"\n|- style=\"border-bottom: 3px solid #AA1527;\"\n! style=\"width:5em;\"  | No.<br />overall\n! style=\"width:5em;\"  | No. in<br />season\n! Title\n! Directed by\n! Written by\n! style=\"width:12em;\" | Original air date<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s.mxtv.jp/anime/kakegurui/|title=\u8ced\u30b1\u30b0\u30eb\u30a4|work=[[Tokyo MX]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 1\n| Title               = A Woman Named Yumeko Jabami\n| TranslitTitle       = Jabami Yumeko to Iu Onna\n| NativeTitle         = \u86c7\u55b0\u5922\u5b50\u3068\u3044\u3046\u5973\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| DirectedBy          = Y\u016bichir\u014d Hayashi\n| WrittenBy           = [[Yasuko Kobayashi]]\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2017|7|1}}\n| ShortSummary        = Shiritsu Hyakkaou Academy is one of Japan's most prestigious schools, where only the rich can enter. However, unlike normal schools, this one is run entirely by the Student Council and possesses a frightening hierarchy determined by gambling. There, the best gamblers enjoy popularity, money, connections and authority, while those in debt are deemed as Pets and servants to the entire student body, recognisable with a chain and tag around their neck. Yumeko Jabami, a beautiful but mysterious second-year transfer student, arrives at Hyakkaou Academy and is introduced to the school by Ryota Suzui, a male student who has been classified as a bottom-ranked Pet after having lost a gamble to Mary Saotome, their class's best gambler, and hence accumulating a large debt. As Ryota warns Yumeko of the gambling system and discourages her from gambling, Mary challenges Yumeko to a [[Rock paper scissors|modified rock-paper-scissors]] game: (''[[Jankenpon]]''). Although Yumeko loses all her chips, she requests a final bet worth 10 million yen in cash, and reveals how Mary had manipulated the classmates' votes to allow her to determine Yumeko's cards. Yumeko mocks Mary for giving away her methods and then wins the game, placing Mary into debt. Afterwards, Ryota apologises to Yumeko for his role in helping Mary cheat, but Yumeko gifts him some of her winnings as thanks for adding to the thrill of the game and considers him her friend.\n| LineColor           = AA1527\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 2\n| Title               = A Boring Woman\n| TranslitTitle       = Tsumannai Onna\n| NativeTitle         = \u3064\u307e\u3093\u306a\u3044\u5973\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| DirectedBy          = Takashi Kobayashi\n| WrittenBy           = Yasuko Kobayashi\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2017|7|8}}\n| ShortSummary        = Follow her loss, Mary becomes a Pet. Yumeko, whose name has been spread all over the school for having beat Mary on her first day after her transfer, is challenged to a Double Concentration game by Itsuki Sumeragi, the daughter of the CEO of Japan's top toy company and a first-year member of the Student Council, famed for having never lost at a card game before. For this gamble, Itsuki uses two decks of cards \"Radcliffe\" made by her father's company and wins 20 million yen from Yumeko in a close match. Despite Yumeko not having enough money and Itsuki having won already, Itsuki decides to accept a second round under the condition that if Yumeko loses she can have her fingernails and toenails removed to add to her already extensive nail collection. Once again, Itsuki deals from the same two decks, confident that her cheating style of using heat-activated patterns in the cards will help her win again. However, Yumeko reveals to have picked up on her scheme since the first game and used her intellect to memorise the cards and match them to their corresponding matching card, winning the game on her first turn and remarking that Itsuki would have won had she used cards with different markings.\n| LineColor           = AA1527\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 3\n| Title               = Slit-Eyed Woman\n| TranslitTitle       = Itome no Onna\n| NativeTitle         = \u7cf8\u76ee\u306e\u5973\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| DirectedBy          = [[Shigeru Ueda]]\n| WrittenBy           = Yasuko Kobayashi\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2017|7|15}}\n| ShortSummary        = Yumeko is invited to the Traditional Culture Research Society's clubroom just in time to witness Mary lose a high-stakes bet and adding 40 million yen to her debt. Yuriko Nishinot\u014din, Mary's opponent, a Student Council member and president of the Culture Club, then challenges Yumeko to the Life or Death game, introducing her to the only right of the Pets: to challenge anybody of their choosing to an \"official match\", which Mary had done just now. After the first game ends in a draw, Yumeko goes all in, deducing that Yuriko has been cheating by having the dealer wear magnets on her hand to affect the movement of the swords. Just as Yuriko becomes panicked over the thought of potentially losing over 2 billion yen, several Student Council members, including the Student Council President Kirari Momobami, step in suddenly to observe the game. When the swords are unveiled, it reveals Yuriko's win, which Yumeko suspects may have been the result of an elaborate cheating method the Student Council used specifically for their game, by heading directly to the room underneath and using magnets to prevent her 